---
description: Testing and code quality rules
alwaysApply: true
---

Testing philosophy:
- Write production-quality code with tests for critical behavior.
- Prefer deterministic unit tests for business logic (call analysis, deal prediction, lead routing).
- Add integration tests for APIs, repositories, pipelines, and workflows crossing boundaries.
- Mock external services: Twilio, OpenAI, Redis, PostgreSQL (or use test containers).

Backend testing (Python — Pytest):
- Use pytest + pytest-asyncio for async test support.
- Use httpx.AsyncClient with ASGITransport for API endpoint tests.
- Fixtures in backend/tests/conftest.py for database sessions, test users, tenants, auth headers.
- Mock OpenAI responses for transcript/analysis tests (avoid live API calls in CI).
- Mock Twilio webhooks and media streams for call pipeline tests.
- Test Celery tasks independently with mocked dependencies.

Frontend testing (TypeScript — Vitest):
- Use Vitest + React Testing Library for component and hook tests.
- Use @playwright/test for end-to-end tests.
- Test critical flows: login, call initiation, real-time panel updates, deal prediction display.
- Mock API responses and Socket.IO events in tests.

Code quality:
- Use linting (ruff for Python, ESLint for TypeScript) and formatting.
- Use types everywhere; Python type hints and TypeScript strict mode.
- Keep functions focused; refactor repeated logic into shared utilities when justified.

Do not:
- Add major logic without at least basic tests.
- Create brittle tests tied to unstable implementation details.
- Depend on live Twilio, OpenAI, or external APIs in normal test runs.
- Skip testing auth and permission-sensitive flows.
